@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{nado}}}} is used to terminate a non-exhaustive list of nouns. It is often used in conjunction
with <a href="grammar-particle-ya.html">@HI{{ya}}</a>.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha,@KT{{ringo}}yamikannyabanana@EM{{nado}},kudamononara@KJ{{what}}demo@KJ{{fond}}kidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I like any kind of fruit: apples, oranges, bananas.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{nado}}}} can be used to indicate a tentative suggestion.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come^week}}no@KJ{{trip^going}}ha@KJ{{box^root}}@EM{{nado}}doudesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How about Hakone for next week's trip?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
If the main predicate is negated, @HI{{@EM{{nado}}}} can indicate a sense of humbleness.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{kon'no@FG{{@KJ{{flip^translate}}:hon'yaku}}shitekudasaimasenka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{kon'na@KJ{{difficult}}shiimono,@KJ{{private}}@EM{{nado}}niha@KJ{{exit^come}}masen'.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Could you kindly translate this for me?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: A person like me cannot translate such a difficult thing.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="contempt">@HI{{@EM{{nado}}}}</a> can convey a sense of contempt.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{person}}no@KJ{{say}}ttakoto@EM{{nado}}@KJ{{spirit}}nisurukotohaarimasen'.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I pay no attention to anything he says.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="negative">@HI{{@EM{{nado}}}}</a> can emphasise the negative aspect of a situation, especially in a belittling manner.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{rice*field^in}}:tanaka}}san@EM{{nado}}ha,totemo@FG{{@KJ{{company^long}}:shachou}}nihanarenai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There's no way that anyone like Tanaka could become president of the company.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="impossible">@HI{{@EM{{nado}}}}</a> can emphasise the impossibility of the situation.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{son'na@KJ{{tall}}imono@EM{{nado}},itadakuwakenihaikimasen.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I could never accept such an expensive gift.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

